<subsection xml:id="C3.S9.SS5">
<title>Levin’s and Weniger’s Transformations</title>           
<para xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="98" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.s1">
We give a special form of Levin’s transformation in which the sequence <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.m1">s=\{s_{n}\}</Math> of partial sums <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.m2">s_{n}=\sum_{j=0}^{n}a_{j}</Math> is transformed into: <Math equation-number="3.9.13" mode="display" xml:id="C3.S9.E13">{\cal L}_{k}^{(n)}(s)=\frac{\sum_{j=0}^{k}(-1)^{j}\genfrac{(}{)}{0.0pt}{}{k}{j }c_{j,k,n}\ifrac{s_{n+j}}{a_{n+j+1}}}{\sum_{j=0}^{k}(-1)^{j}\genfrac{(}{)}{0.0 pt}{}{k}{j}c_{j,k,n}/a_{n+j+1}},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.m3">k</Math> is a fixed nonnegative integer, and <Math equation-number="3.9.14" mode="display" xml:id="C3.S9.E14">c_{j,k,n}=\frac{(n+j+1)^{k-1}}{(n+k+1)^{k-1}}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="99" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.s2">
Sequences that are accelerated by Levin’s transformation includelogarithmically convergent sequences, i.e., sequences <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.m4">s_{n}</Math> converging to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p1.m5">\sigma</Math> such that <Math equation-number="3.9.15" mode="display" xml:id="C3.S9.E15">\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{s_{n+1}-\sigma}{s_{n}-\sigma}=1</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="100" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p2.s1">
For further information see Brezinski and Redivo Zaglia (1991, pp. 39–42).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="101" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.s1">
In Weniger’s transformations the numbers <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.m1">c_{j,k,n}</Math> in (3.9.13) are chosen as follows: <Math equation-number="3.9.16" mode="display" xml:id="C3.S9.E16">c_{j,k,n}=\frac{{\left(\beta+n+j\right)_{k-1}}}{{\left(\beta+n+k\right)_{k-1}}},</Math> or <Math equation-number="3.9.17" mode="display" xml:id="C3.S9.E17">c_{j,k,n}=\frac{{\left(-\gamma-n-j\right)_{k-1}}}{{\left(-\gamma-n-k\right)_{k -1}}},</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.m2">{\left(a\right)_{0}}=1</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.m3">{\left(a\right)_{j}}=a(a+1)\cdots(a+j-1)</Math> are Pochhammer symbols (§5.2(iii)), and the constants <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.m4">\beta</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.m5">\gamma</Math> are chosen arbitrarily subject to certain conditions.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="102" xml:id="C3.S9.SS5.p3.s2">
See Weniger (1989).
</sentence>

</para>
 
